<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena sparsipunctata" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sparsipunctata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Andrena sparsipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily placed into the 
<taxonomicName authority="Dours, 1873" authorityName="Dours" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Campylogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Campylogaster" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Campylogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the large, dense, and clear punctures on the episternum combined with its large body size. However, recent evidence shows that 
<taxonomicName authority="Dours, 1873" authorityName="Dours" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Campylogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Campylogaster" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Campylogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is strongly polyphyletic, and the species in northwestern Africa do not fall close to 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. (Campylogaster) erberi" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="erberi" subGenus="Campylogaster">A. (Campylogaster) erberi</taxonomicName>
Morawitz, 1871, the type species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Dours, 1873" authorityName="Dours" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Campylogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Campylogaster" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Campylogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that differs by its tormentose pilosity. A new subgenus is probably needed for the species around 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. sparsipunctata" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="sparsipunctata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. sparsipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1101/2020.06.09.103556" author="Pisanty, G" journalOrPublisher="Gounouilhou, Bordeaux" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B28" refString="Pisanty, G, Richter, R, Martin, T, Dettman, J, Cardinal, S, 2020. Molecular phylogeny and historical biogeography of andrenine bees (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae). bioRxiv. https://doi.org/10.1101/2020.06.09.103556" title="Molecular phylogeny and historical biogeography of andrenine bees (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae). bioRxiv." url="https://doi.org/10.1101/2020.06.09.103556" year="2020">Pisanty et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Against this context, it is close to the two most widespread 
<taxonomicName authority="Dours, 1873" authorityName="Dours" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Campylogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Campylogaster" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Campylogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in North Africa, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. pruinosa subsp. succinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="subSpecies" species="pruinosa" subSpecies="succinea">A. pruinosa Erichson, 1835 ssp. succinea</taxonomicName>
Dours, 1872 and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. caroli" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="caroli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. caroli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
, 1895, both of which are also stained red over the majority of the metasoma. The female of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. sparsipunctata" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="sparsipunctata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. sparsipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is instantly recognisable because the punctures of the first tergite are sparse, separated by 2-4 puncture diameters (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">16</figureCitation>
) whereas in the other two species the punctures are dense and separated by 1-2 puncture diameters (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">18</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">20</figureCitation>
). Moreover, the foveae of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. sparsipunctata" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="sparsipunctata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. sparsipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females are narrow and depart from the inner eye margins so that at the top of the compound eye they are separated from the compound eye by a distance subequal to the width of a fovea itself (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">15</figureCitation>
), whereas in the other two species the foveae are never clearly separated from the top of the compound eye (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">17</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">19</figureCitation>
). The scutal hairs are also normal, not squamous (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">15</figureCitation>
), strongly contrasting with the squamous hairs of the other two species (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">17</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">19</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
